To open a URL and inject code into it using HTML and JS, you can use the `window.open()` method to open the URL in a new window, and then use the `document.write()` method to inject the code into the opened window.

Example:

HTML:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>My Page</title>
	<script src="script.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
	<h1>Welcome to my page!</h1>
	<button onclick="openNewPage()">Click me</button>
</body>
</html>
```

JS (script.js):

```
function openNewPage() {
	// open new window with URL and name
	var newWindow = window.open("https://www.google.com", "My Window");

	// wait for the new window to load
	newWindow.onload = function() {
		// execute the code to be injected
		var script = "window.alert('Injected code executed on new page');";

		// write the script to the new window
		newWindow.document.write("<script>" + script + "</script>");
	};
}
```

In this example, when the user clicks the button, the `openNewPage()` function is called, which opens the specified URL in a new window using `window.open()`. When the new page has finished loading, the function executes the desired code to be injected into the page and injects it using the `document.write()` method.

Note that injecting code into a new window using `document.write()` can have unintended consequences, such as overwriting the existing content of the opened window. Additionally, some browsers may block pop-ups or block calls to `document.write()`. Therefore, it's important to use this technique judiciously and test it thoroughly across different browsers.

